      "content": "A larger needle can sometimes make things worse, especially if the fabric is prone to splitting. In that case, trying a different stabilizer might be a good idea. You could try using a piece of evenweave linen or a silk-specific interfacing to provide extra support and stability to the fabric. It's a bit like giving the fabric a gentle hand, rather than trying to wrestle it into submission. \n\nAs for feeding the fabric through, you might want to try using a walking foot or a Teflon foot to help guide the fabric smoothly and prevent bunching. This can be especially helpful when working with delicate or slippery fabrics like silk. It's a bit like navigating a narrow, winding path through a dense forest - you need to be gentle and deliberate to avoid getting lost or caught on obstacles.",
